english:
  title: Record of the Reconstruction of Bamboo Staff Hermitage on Mi-ji Mountain in Chi-pyong County
  author: Lee Sack
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Monk Gak-jo came to my door seeking something. He said, "Chi-pyong's Dragon Gate Mountain is well known to the world, and its name is Mi-ji. There once stood a hermitage here called Gaehyeon. One who dwelt there and attained enlightenment left us his name forgotten, though he received a bamboo staff as a royal gift, and so the hermitage came to be called Bamboo Staff Hermitage—thus it has been passed down among mountain folk.

    This hermitage rests upon the heights of the mountain as if upon the heart itself, while the upper temple sits at the navel. Thus the hermitage stands luminous and clear, rising above the verdant veil of forest. Gazing down, Chiak Mountain and the Li River seem cradled in the palm of one's hand. The nearby peaks bow low, encircling left and right—towering yet graceful, lovely and worthy of contemplation. The seasons turn, light and shadow dance their eternal change—yet words fail them entirely.

    When facing the wall, the heart grows cold as ash, emotions and landscape both fade away. The practitioner sits in deep solitude, which troubles the seeker. Yet when rising from meditation, robes rustled high and eyebrows raised, a wisp of cloud and passing bird join a single expanse of azure ten thousand leagues wide. Mountains become screens, the river becomes silk unfurled, mirroring and framing left and right. The eye's horizon opens clear, the mind's source shines bright. All doubt dissolves, all karmic veils vanish.

    Consider the afflicted man who cannot walk—with a staff he rises and walks strong. So too does landscape kindle mind, and mind reveals the Way. In this place where effort matters most, there is a wordless accord. How much more so with the bamboo, whose hollow center yields to the gentlest touch?

    This is why I undertake this reconstruction of the hermitage."

    Gak-jo continued: "When I first set my heart upon this place, I had no patron, no support. Then fortune brought Madam Won, wife of Official Yu, to the mountains. I shared my vision with her, and she, moved by joy, became the patron of this deed. Beginning in the third month of spring in the Year of Ding-si, work commenced and was completed by the seventh month of autumn. Painting and decoration finished in the ninth month, and the hermitage was dedicated in the tenth. Though merely three rooms, the Buddha dwells within and monks dwell on either side—how does this differ from the great temples? When a single person awakens to truth and returns to the source, all the ten directions and empty space dissolve away. The number of monks and the size of buildings are matters beyond our discourse. I beg you, master, to grace us with words to form this record."

    I replied: "Gak-jo has transcended the illusions of the human world and has already entered the dharma with his body. Let him seek the profound essence to uphold in his mind, making it a place of adamantine indestructibility—such is the urgency! A single meditation seat, when viewed as containing all three thousand worlds, makes the great and small self-defined. Yet the arising and dissolution of the three thousand worlds does not escape the four-inch mind. To seek the four-inch mind, one must find it in that single meditation seat. Once found there, how could such a seat be deemed small? This is why Hansan writes this record. Let those who read it hereafter refrain from mockery.

    Written in the fifth month of the year Ki-mi."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Hansan (韓山子) is a literary sobriquet for the author, Lee Sack, referencing Mount Hansan.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three thousand great thousand worlds' (三千大千世界) is a Buddhist cosmological concept representing all possible worlds and experiences.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'four-inch mind' (方촌心) refers to the fundamental human consciousness in its smallest, most essential form—the seat of enlightenment.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'single meditation seat' symbolizes the smallest possible space where profound spiritual realization can occur.
